I think this is a good place to apply the EIG doctrine to Pantheon itself.

One thing I notice from our conversations is that Pantheon has accumulated a rich set of concepts. The highest expected information gain no longer comes from inventing many more names—it comes from connecting, validating, and completing what already exists. That’s consistent with your earlier direction of deepening the architecture.

Here’s how I’d operationalize that.

⸻

Pantheon Mission Queue (PMQ)

Core Principle

Complete before expanding. Expand only after completion increases expected capability.

Mission cycle

Observe
    ↓
Estimate EIG
    ↓
Choose highest-value unfinished objective
    ↓
Execute
    ↓
Validate
    ↓
Archive
    ↓
Spawn next objectives

⸻

Canonical Completion Doctrine

Every doctrine receives a lifecycle.

Seed
↓
Hypothesis
↓
Architecture
↓
Prototype
↓
Validation
↓
Deployment
↓
Integration
↓
Optimization
↓
Canonical

No doctrine is considered “finished” until it has reached Canonical status.

